title: On the cohomology of the Bigolin complex

sections.text:
#### Abstract

Given a compact complex manifold, we develop Hodge theory for the elliptic complex of differential forms defined by Bigolin in 1969 and recently referred as the Schweitzer complex. We exhibit several $L^{2}$ orthogonal decompositions of spaces of forms and prove a Hodge decomposition for harmonic forms on compact Kähler manifolds. Then we compute the cohomology of this Bigolin complex on the small deformations of the complex structure of the Iwasawa manifold, showing that, in this example, this Bigolin cohomology is as powerful as Aeppli and Bott-Chern cohomology, in order to distinguish complex structures. Recall that the double complex of a compact complex manifold decomposes into a direct sum of so-called squares and zigzags, and the zigzags are the only components contributing to cohomology. We prove that, on any compact complex manifold of complex dimension 3, the multiplicities of zigzags in this decomposition are completely characterised by Betti, Hodge, Aeppli numbers plus Bigolin numbers, namely the dimensions of the Bigolin cohomology. This result is sharp, meaning that if we remove Hodge or Bigolin numbers from the previous statement then it becomes false. We then apply this last result to fully describe the double complexes of the small deformations of the Iwasawa manifold. Finally, we partially extend the definition of this complex on almost complex manifolds, providing a cohomological invariant on 1-forms which is finite dimensional when the manifold is compact.

## 1. Introduction

Given a complex manifold $M$, the exterior derivative on $(p, q)$-forms splits as

$$
d=\partial+\bar{\partial}: A^{p, q} \rightarrow A^{p+1, q} \otimes A^{p, q+1}
$$

so that $d^{2}=0$ implies the relations

$$
\partial^{2}=\bar{\partial}^{2}=\partial \bar{\partial}+\bar{\partial} \partial=0
$$

Therefore, there are natural complexes of differential forms arising on $M$. The simplest is the Dolbeault complex

$$
\ldots \longrightarrow A^{p, q-1} \xrightarrow{\partial} A^{p, q} \xrightarrow{\partial} A^{p, q+1} \longrightarrow \ldots
$$

together with its conjugate

$$
\ldots \longrightarrow A^{p-1, q} \xrightarrow{\partial} A^{p, q} \xrightarrow{\partial} A^{p+1, q} \longrightarrow \ldots
$$

The associated cohomology spaces are the Dolbeault cohomology and the $\partial$ cohomology

$$
H_{\partial}^{p, q}:=\frac{\operatorname{ker} \bar{\partial} \cap A^{p, q}}{\bar{\partial} A^{p, q-1}}, \quad H_{\partial}^{p, q}:=\frac{\operatorname{ker} \partial \cap A^{p, q}}{\partial A^{p-1, q}}
$$

There is another natural complex, which will be the main subject of this paper
![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)
and which, in these notes, may be referred as the Bigolin complex, for reasons which hopefully will become clear soon. Its complete definition is given in Section 2.

We provide a short historical review of the study of the Bigolin complex. It was introduced by Bigolin in [Big69, Big70] as a tool to study the Aeppli and Bott-Chern cohomology groups

$$
H_{A}^{p, q}:=\frac{\operatorname{ker} \partial \bar{\partial} \cap A^{p, q}}{\partial A^{p-1, q}+\bar{\partial} A^{p, q-1}}, \quad H_{B C}^{p+1, q+1}:=\frac{\operatorname{ker} d \cap A^{p+1, q+1}}{\partial \bar{\partial} A^{p, q}}
$$

i.e., the cohomology of the central part of the complex (1), namely the shorter complex given by the map $\partial \bar{\partial}$ and the two adjacent ones. Notice that in [Big69, proof of Teorema 2.1] it is proved that the cohomology of the complex (1) is finite on compact complex manifolds. Later, the hypercohomology of the complex (1) was studied by Demailly ${ }^{1}$ in his book [Dem12, Chapter VI, Section 12] and by Schweitzer in his thesis [Sch07, Section 4]. In [Dem12, Chapter VI, proof of Theorem 12.4] there is a second proof of the finite dimensionality of the cohomology of the complex (1) on compact complex manifolds.

Recently, the complex (1) has been the central subject of the paper [Ste25] by Stelzig, where it is referred as the Schweitzer complex. Stelzig shows that the Schweitzer complex is elliptic [Ste25, Lemma 2.4] (this provides a third proof of the finite dimensionality of the cohomology of the complex (1) on compact complex manifolds), proves an index theorem [Ste25, Theorem 2.8] and other fundamental properties like Poincaré duality [Ste25, Corollary C]. In [MS24], a generalised version of Massey products has been defined starting from this Schweitzer complex. The cohomology spaces arising from the Schweitzer complex appear also in [Ste23]. This complex is then considered in [YY23] to study bimeromorphic invariants associated to Bott-Chern hypercohomology. A related $L^{2}$ Hilbert complex has been defined in [HP23], where (1) is called Aeppli-Bott-Chern complex, since the focus of the paper is the central part of the complex and its $L^{2}$ cohomology.

Apart from the above mentioned works, the Bigolin complex has received very little attention, as noticed also in [Ste25]. For instance, in the literature there are no

explicit examples of calculation of Bigolin numbers, namely the dimensions of the Bigolin cohomology spaces, i.e., of the cohomology of the Bigolin complex. The only well studied part of the complex is the central part, related to Aeppli and Bott-Chern cohomology. In view of these considerations, the main purposes of this paper are the following: to settle the fundamental Hodge theoretic properties of the extremal parts of the Bigolin complex; to compute the cohomological invariants of the Bigolin complex on examples of compact complex manifolds; to provide evidence that these Bigolin numbers are useful to describe the double complex of differential $(p, q)$-forms associated to a compact complex manifold; finally to suggest the study of a new cohomological invariant related to 1-forms which can be defined on compact almost complex manifolds. Meanwhile, we present several graphic representations of the Bigolin complex, hoping for an easier understanding of its nature.

The paper is organised as follows. In Section 2, for every choice of a bidegree $(p, q)$ on a complex manifold $M$, we define the Bigolin complex, denoted by $\left(\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet}, \delta_{p, q}^{\bullet}\right)$, its cohomology

$$
H_{p, q}^{\bullet}:=\frac{\operatorname{ker} \delta_{p, q}^{\bullet} \cap \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet}}{\delta_{p, q}^{\bullet} \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet-1}}
$$

and report some immediate properties. There is no original material in this section other than, possibly, the observations contained in Remarks 2.9 and 2.10.

Section 3 is first devoted to the definition of the elliptic operators

$$
\square_{p, q}^{k}: \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k} \rightarrow \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k}
$$

which are naturally associated to the elliptic complex (cf. [Ste25, Proof of Corollary D], [HP23, Section 2], [Var86, Section 1]). Given a Hermitian metric $g$ on $M$, the operator $\square_{p, q}^{k}$ is defined via the differential

$$
\delta_{p, q}^{k}: \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k} \rightarrow \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k+1}
$$

and its formal adjoint

$$
\left(\delta_{p, q}^{k}\right)^{*}: \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k+1} \rightarrow \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k}
$$

Once the manifold $M$ is compact, then

$$
\operatorname{ker} \square_{p, q}^{k}=\operatorname{ker} \delta_{p, q}^{k} \cap \operatorname{ker}\left(\delta_{p, q}^{k-1}\right)^{*}=H_{p, q}^{k}
$$

and it has finite dimension $h_{p, q}^{k}$. Furthermore, Hodge theory provides several $L^{2}$ orthogonal decompositions of the spaces of forms $\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k}$.
Theorem 1.1 (see Remark 3.4). Given a compact Hermitian manifold $(M, g)$, there are $L^{2}$ orthogonal decompositions

$$
\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k}=\operatorname{ker} \square_{p, q}^{k} \oplus \delta_{p, q}^{k-1} \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k-1} \oplus\left(\delta_{p, q}^{k}\right)^{*} \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k+1}
$$

We also show that the Hodge * operator and conjugation induce a symmetry for the invariants $h_{p, q}^{k}$ and consequently for the Euler characteristic $\chi_{p, q}$ of the complex, namely

$$
\begin{aligned}
h_{p, q}^{k} & =h_{n-q-1, n-p-1}^{2 n-k-1}=h_{n-p-1, n-q-1}^{2 n-k-1}=h_{q, p}^{k} \\
\chi_{p, q} & =-\chi_{n-q-1, n-p-1}=-\chi_{n-p-1, n-q-1}=\chi_{q, p}
\end{aligned}
$$

This symmetry is also proved in [Ste25, Corollary C] by another method ${ }^{2}$.
We recall that on a compact Kähler manifold we have the Hodge decomposition for de Rham harmonic forms: $\operatorname{ker} \Delta_{d} \cap A_{\mathbb{C}}^{k}=\oplus_{p+q=k} \operatorname{ker} \Delta_{\bar{\partial}} \cap A^{p, q}$, where $\Delta_{D}=$ $D D^{*}+D^{*} D$ and $D^{*}$ denotes the formal adjoint of $D$ for $D \in\{d, \bar{\partial}\}$. By applying Kähler identities, we are able to prove the following Hodge decomposition for the harmonic forms of the complex $\left(\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet}, \delta_{p, q}^{\bullet}\right)$.

Theorem 1.2 (see Theorem 3.11). Given a compact Kähler manifold $(M, g)$, it holds

$$
\operatorname{ker} \square_{p, q}^{k}=\operatorname{ker} \Delta_{\bar{\partial}} \cap \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k}
$$

The proof is achieved thanks to a formula relating the Laplacians $\square_{p, q}^{k}$ and $\Delta_{\bar{\partial}}$ in Remark 3.10. Notice that this formula has already proved to be useful in other settings. In fact, it is a generalisation of another formula in [HP23, proof of Theorem 8.8], which is a step into proving spectral gap conditions of the Bott-Chern Laplacian on complete Kähler manifolds.

The cohomological implications of Theorem 1.2 are not a novelty, as it is explained in Remark 3.12, while the theorem itself is original. The other Hodge theoretic content of Section 3, including Theorem 1.1, is a simple application of standard Hodge theory to the Bigolin complex (cf. [Ste25, proofs of Corollaries B, D]). Nevertheless, this content is not available elsewhere in the literature and thus we think that its presentation in these notes may be convenient for further studies.

In Section 4 we make use of recent results of [Ste21, Ste25, Ste23] in order to explicitly compute the Bigolin numbers $h_{p, q}^{k}$ of the small deformations of the Iwasawa manifold reducing the problem to a linear algebra calculation. The Dolbeault cohomology of these small deformations were computed in [Nak75], while the Aeppli and Bott-Chern cohomology in [Ang13]. It has been proved that in this example Aeppli and Bott-Chern cohomology can distinguish between complex structures more precisely than Dolbeault cohomology, providing finer invariants. Here we show that, in this example, the Bigolin cohomology $H_{p, q}^{k}$ is as powerful as Aeppli and Bott-Chern cohomology, in order to distinguish classes of complex structures.

In Section 5 we provide evidence that the Bigolin numbers $h_{p, q}^{k}$ are useful to characterise double complexes of compact complex manifolds. It is well known that the double complex $\left(A^{\bullet \bullet \bullet}, \partial, \bar{\partial}\right)$ of a compact complex manifold decomposes into direct sum of so-called squares and finitely many zigzags. The zigzags are the only components contributing to cohomology. More precisely, in [Ste21, Proposition 6 and Lemma 8] it is shown how every zigzag contributes to de Rham, Dolbeault, $\partial$-, Aeppli and Bott-Chern cohomology. The analogue result for the Bigolin cohomology is Proposition 5.6.

We consider a compact complex manifold of complex dimension 3 and classify 17 different shapes of zigzags ( 18 if we include the dot counting the connected components of the manifold) which exhaust all the possible zigzags modulo conjugation and duality. We then describe how these zigzags contribute to the Bigolin cohomology $H_{p, q}^{k}$ and are actually able to invert these contributes "zigzags $\Longrightarrow$ cohomology" as follows.

Theorem 1.3 (see Theorem 5.7). Given a compact complex 3-manifold, the multiplicities of the zigzags in the direct sum decomposition of the double complex $\left(A^{\bullet \bullet \bullet}, \partial, \bar{\partial}\right)$ are completely characterised by the invariants $h_{\partial}^{p, q}, h_{A}^{p, q}, b^{k}$ and $h_{p, q}^{k}$ for all $p, q, k$.

This result is sharp, meaning that if we remove either the Bigolin numbers $h_{p, q}^{k}$ or the Hodge numbers $h_{\partial}^{p, q}$ from the statement then it becomes false, as it is shown respectively in Remarks 5.9 and 5.10. In particular, this answers the following question posed by Jonas Stelzig in a private communication: "If we know the dimensions of all Bigolin cohomology groups, can we calculate the multiplicities of all zigzags?". We restrict our analysis to compact complex manifolds of complex dimension 3 for simplicity and since it is sufficient to our applications, but we do not see any reason preventing generalising Theorem 1.3 into higher dimensions, although computational complexity rapidly grows. We would like to deal with this

problem in the future. In complex dimension 2 the double complexes have more restrictions, as explained in [Ste21, Remark 19], therefore the situation is simpler.

Finally, Section 6 is devoted to a partial generalisation of the elliptic complex (1) in the case of almost complex manifolds. We observe that there are elliptic complexes

$$
\begin{gathered}
A^{0,0} \xrightarrow{d} A^{0,1} \oplus A^{1,0} \xrightarrow{\partial \oplus \bar{\partial}} A^{1,1} \\
A^{n-1, n-1} \xrightarrow{d} A^{n-1, n} \oplus A^{n, n-1} \xrightarrow{d} A^{n, n}
\end{gathered}
$$

which provide new invariants of almost complex manifolds. The cohomology of these complexes are

$$
\begin{gathered}
H_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}:=\frac{\operatorname{ker} \partial \oplus \bar{\partial} \cap A^{0,1} \oplus A^{1,0}}{d A^{0,0}} \\
H_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1}:=\frac{\operatorname{ker} d \cap A^{n-1, n} \oplus A^{n, n-1}}{d A^{n-1, n-1}}
\end{gathered}
$$

and when the manifold is compact they have finite dimension $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}=h_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1}$, since they are isomorphic to the kernels of elliptic operators. To the knowledge of the author, the invariant $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}$ is the only finite invariant of the (non integrable) almost complex structure of a compact manifold which is cohomological (it is the dimension of the cohomology space of an elliptic differential complex). In Remark 6.8 we discuss about two other invariants defined in [PT22, ST23] on 1-forms which are only trivially cohomological ${ }^{34}$.

This problem of finding finite invariants of compact almost complex manifolds which are cohomological is strictly related to the following problem of interest in the last few years. Denote by $h_{\bar{\partial}}^{\mathrm{p}, q}$ the dimension of the Dolbeault cohomology $H_{\bar{\partial}}^{\mathrm{p}, q} \simeq$ $\operatorname{ker} \Delta_{\bar{\partial}} \cap A^{p, q}$ of a compact complex manifold. Problem 20 by Kodaira and Spencer in [Hir54] basically asks: "given a compact almost complex manifold $(M, J)$ endowed with an almost Hermitian metric $g$, is the number $h_{\bar{\partial}}^{\mathrm{p}, q}:=\operatorname{dim}_{\mathbb{C}} \operatorname{ker} \Delta_{\bar{\partial}} \cap A^{p, q}$ metric independent (as in the case of complex manifolds)? In case it is not independent, give a generalisation of the $h_{\bar{\partial}}^{p, q}$ of a complex manifold depending only on $(M, J)$." The first part of the problem has been solved in [HZ22] and later in [TT23], where it is shown that $h_{\bar{\partial}}^{p, q}$ depends on the metric. Concerning the second part of the problem, in [CW21] a Dolbeault cohomology for almost complex manifolds has been defined, but in [CPS22] it is shown that it can be infinite dimensional even when $M$ is compact. Different Aeppli and Bott-Chern-like finite dimensional (when $M$ is compact) invariants have been defined as the dimension of the kernel of elliptic operators in [PT22, ST23], but in general they depend on the metric.

Given a compact manifold, Hodge theory provides an isomorphism between the kernel of an elliptic operator, defined via the combination of a metric independent elliptic complex and a metric, and the cohomology of the complex itself. In this way, a metric independent elliptic complex gives rise to metric independent and finite invariants of the compact manifold. However, the problem on almost complex manifolds is that the conditions $\partial^{2} \neq 0, \bar{\partial}^{2} \neq 0, \partial \bar{\partial}+\bar{\partial} \partial \neq 0$ drastically reduce the number of elliptic complexes. For this reason $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}$, being defined via a metric independent elliptic complex, is a notable exception.

# 2. The COMPLEX Definition 2.1 (The Bigolin complex). Given a complex manifold $M$ of complex dimension $n$, for each bidegree $(p, q)$ with $-1 \leq p, q \leq n$, we define a complex $\left(\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet}, \delta_{p, q}^{\bullet}\right)$ of differential forms. Denoting by $A^{r, s}$ the space of $(r, s)$-forms, and by $d$ the exterior derivative, for every $0 \leq k \leq 2 n-1$ we set $$ \begin{array}{ll} \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k}:=\bigoplus_{\substack{r \rightarrow s=k \\ 0 \leq r \leq p \\ 0 \leq s \leq q}} A^{r, s} & k \leq p+q \\ \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k}:=\bigoplus_{\substack{r \rightarrow s=k+1 \\ q \leq r \leq n \\ qp+q \end{array} $$ with differentials $\delta_{p, q}^{k}: \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k} \rightarrow \mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k+1}$ defined by $$ \begin{array}{ll} \delta_{p, q}^{k}=\pi_{\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k+1}} \circ d & kp+q \end{array} $$ where $\pi_{\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k}}$ is the natural projection from $A_{r}^{\bullet}:=A^{\bullet} \otimes \mathbb{C}$ to $\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{k}$. The complex $\left(\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet}, \delta_{p, q}^{\bullet}\right)$ will be referred as the Bigolin complex. Note that our definition of $\left(\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet}, \delta_{p, q}^{\bullet}\right)$ is shifted in the indexes $(p, q)$ with respect to the definitions of [Sch07, Dem12, Ste25]: denoting by $\left(\mathcal{L}_{p, q}^{\bullet}, d_{p, q}^{\bullet}\right)$ the complex defined in these papers, it holds $\left(\mathcal{L}_{p+1, q+1}^{\bullet}, d_{p+1, q+1}^{\bullet}\right)=\left(\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet}, \delta_{p, q}^{\bullet}\right)$. This shift in the index is motivated by the fact that, thanks to duality, we are interested in studying only the first part of the complex $\left(\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet}, \delta_{p, q}^{\bullet}\right)$, for $0 \leq k \leq p+q$. Remark 2.2 (Extremal cases). The previous definition is not completely precise. In fact, the integer $k$ varies from 0 to $2 n-1$ only for $p+q \neq-2,2 n$, while if $p=q=-1$ then $k$ actually varies from -1 to $2 n-1$, and if $p=q=n$ then $k$ actually varies from 0 to $2 n$. In these extremal cases the complex $\left(\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet}, \delta_{p, q}^{\bullet}\right)$ just defined actually coincides with the de Rham complex $\left(A^{\bullet}, d\right)$. For this reason, in the rest of the paper we will focus on the case $0 \leq k \leq 2 n-1$ and $p+q \neq-2,2 n$. Remark 2.3 (Graphic representation of the complex). # 4. An explicit COMPutation:
THE SMALL DEFORMATIONS OF THE IWASAWA MANIFOLD Definition 4.1 (The Heisenberg group). We denote by $\mathbb{H}(3 ; \mathbb{C})$ the three dimensional Heisenberg group over $\mathbb{C}$ $$ \mathbb{H}(3 ; \mathbb{C}):=\left\{\left(\begin{array}{ccc} 1 & z^{1} & z^{3} \\ 0 & 1 & z^{2} \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{array}\right) \in G L(3 ; \mathbb{C}): z^{1}, z^{2}, z^{3} \in \mathbb{C}\right\} $$ with the product induced by matrix multiplication, and by $\mathbb{H}(3 ; \mathbb{Z}[i])$ the subgroup of $\mathbb{H}(3 ; \mathbb{C})$ where $z^{1}, z^{2}, z^{3}$ lie in $\mathbb{Z}[i]$. One can check that $\mathbb{H}(3 ; \mathbb{C})$ is a connected simply connected complex nilpotent Lie group, with the complex structure induced by $\mathbb{C}^{3}$. # 5. THE DOUBLE COMPLEX OF A COMPLEX 3-MANIFOLD AND COHOMOLOGICAL INVARIANTS 

Given a complex manifold $M^{n}$ of complex dimension $n$, the bigraded vector space $A^{\bullet \bullet}=\oplus_{1 \leq p, q \leq n} A^{p, q}$ endowed with the differentials $\partial$ and $\bar{\partial}$ has the structure of a double complex $\left(A^{\bullet \bullet}, \partial, \bar{\partial}\right)$. We refer to [Ste21] for the formalisation of the statement that every double complex over a field decomposes into so-called squares and zigzags. Note that de Rham, Dolbeault, $\partial$-, Aeppli, Bott-Chern and more in general the $H_{p, q}^{k}$ cohomology spaces vanish on squares [Ste21, Section2] [Ste25, Lemma 2.3], therefore these cohomology spaces depend only on zigzags. In this section, given a complex 3-manifold $M^{3}$, we relate the zigzags of its double complex with the cohomological invariants introduced so far.

Remark 5.1 (The zigzags of a compact complex manifold). Following the beginning of [Ste21, Section 4], there are some restrictions to the shape of a general zigzag on a compact complex manifold of complex dimension $n$. There are symmetries given by conjugation and duality. Furthermore, the dots in position $(0,0)$ and $(n, n)$ are as many as the connected components of the manifold, and there are only dots (and squares) in the corners $(0,0),(n, 0),(0, n),(n, n)$.

This table can be used to write down all the zigzags of a double complex, knowing Betti (except for $b^{3}$ ), Dolbeault and Aeppli numbers plus Bigolin numbers $h_{1,1}^{1}, h_{1,2}^{1}$ and $h_{2,3}^{4}$. One only has to multiply the matrix $U^{-1}$ with a vector containing the requested cohomological invariants. This is done in Remark 5.11.

Remark 5.9 (Necessity of Bigolin numbers $h_{p, q}^{k}$ in Theorem 5.7). By [Ang13] there are complex structures on the same smooth 6-manifold with the same numbers $h_{\beta}^{p, q}$

Actually, we can show that the statement of Theorem 5.7 is false if we remove $h_{p, q}^{k}$ from it. By [Ste22, Section 9], for every zigzag A,B,C,E,$\ldots$,S (all except for D, for which the result is not known) there is a compact complex manifold where that zigzag occurs in the double complex. Taking the disjoint union of these manifolds, we obtain a compact complex manifold $M$ which is not connected where all the 16 zigzags $\mathrm{A}, \mathrm{B}, \mathrm{C}, \mathrm{E}, \ldots, \mathrm{S}$ occur in the double complex while D does not occur. Removing the column corresponding to D and the row corresponding to $h_{1,2}^{1}$ from

the 17 x 17 matrix $U$ of Remark 5.8, we are left with a 16x16 matrix $U_{1}$ whose rank is 16 . Therefore this manifold $M$ provides the counterexample we need.

More is true. In fact, removing from $U_{1}$ the rows corresponding to $h_{1,1}^{1}$ and $h_{2,3}^{4}$ (this is the same as removing from the matrix $V$ of Remark 5.8 the row corresponding to $b^{3}$ and the column corresponding to $D$ ), we obtain a 14 x 16 matrix $U_{2}$ of rank 14 . The matrix $U_{2}$ represents a linear map sending a vector with multiplicities A,B,C,E,$\ldots$,S to Betti, Dolbeault and Aeppli numbers. Its kernel is 2-dimensional, therefore again by [Ste22, Section 9] we can construct two compact complex manifolds with same Betti, Dolbeault and Aeppli numbers but different Bigolin numbers.

The above problems remain open for connected compact complex manifolds.
Remark 5.10 (Bigolin numbers $h_{p, q}^{k}$ alone do not fully describe zigzags - Necessity of Hodge numbers $h_{\partial}^{p, q}$ in Theorem 5.7). From Remark 2.7 we know that Aeppli (and dually Bott-Chern) cohomology $H_{A}^{p, q}$, de Rham cohomology $H_{d R}^{k}$, and the particular cases of Dolbeault and $\partial$-cohomologies $H_{\partial}^{0, k}$ and $H_{\partial}^{k, 0}$ can be seen as particular cases of Bigolin cohomology $H_{p, q}^{k}$. Actually, this is equivalent to asking if the statement of Theorem 5.7 continues to hold if we remove Hodge numbers $h_{\partial}^{p, q}$ from it. To address such a problem, we remove from the 22 x 17 matrix $T$ of Table 1 the rows corresponding to $h_{\partial}^{0,1}, h_{\partial}^{1,1}$ and $h_{\partial}^{1,2}$, which are the only invariants in the matrix not obtainable as $h_{p, q}^{k}$, finding a 19 x 17 matrix of rank 15 . # 6. Almost complex manifOLDS 

In this section we will consider an almost complex manifold $(M, J)$ of real dimension $2 n$. In general the exterior derivative on $(p, q)$-forms acts as

$$
d: A^{p, q} \rightarrow A^{p+2, q-1} \oplus A^{p+1, q} \oplus A^{p, q+1} \oplus A^{p-1, q+2}
$$

where we denote the four components of $d$ by

$$
d=\mu+\partial+\bar{\partial}+\bar{\mu}
$$

From the relation $d^{2}=0$, we derive

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\mu^{2}=0 \\
\mu \partial+\partial \mu=0 \\
\partial^{2}+\mu \bar{\partial}+\bar{\partial} \mu=0 \\
\frac{\partial \bar{\partial}}{\partial}+\bar{\partial} \partial+\mu \bar{\mu}+\bar{\mu} \mu=0 \\
\bar{\partial}^{2}+\bar{\mu} \partial+\partial \bar{\mu}=0 \\
\bar{\partial} \partial+\bar{\partial} \bar{\mu}=0 \\
\bar{\mu}^{2}=0
\end{array}\right.
$$

Remark 6.1 (Lack of a complete generalisation). If the almost complex structure $J$ is not integrable, there are at least two problems which seem insurmountable in order to define a complete generalisation of the elliptic complex $\left(\mathcal{B}_{p, q}^{\bullet}, \delta_{p, q}^{\bullet}\right)$ of section 2 :
(1) as in the integrable case, we could define the second half of the complex by applying repeatedly the exterior derivative $d$ starting from $A^{p+1, q+1}$ : in general this complex is not elliptic if $J$ is not integrable (one can verify that also the first half of the complex, defined by duality, is not elliptic);

(2) there is no valid replacement for the operator $\partial \bar{\partial}$ for the middle differential of the complex.

Definition 6.2 (A partial generalisation). Since $\partial \bar{\partial}+\bar{\partial} \partial=0$ when applied to $A^{0,0}$ or to $A^{n-1, n-1}$, the following sequences of maps are complexes

$$
\begin{gathered}
A^{0,0} \xrightarrow{d} A^{0,1} \oplus A^{1,0} \xrightarrow{\partial \oplus \bar{\partial}} A^{1,1} \\
A^{n-1, n-1} \xrightarrow{d} A^{n-1, n} \oplus A^{n, n-1} \xrightarrow{d} A^{n, n}
\end{gathered}
$$

which can be verified to be elliptic. In fact, they coincide respectively with the first two maps of the complex $\left(\mathcal{B}_{1,1}^{\bullet}, \delta_{1,1}^{\bullet}\right)$ and with the last two maps of the complex $\left(\mathcal{B}_{n-2, n-2}^{\bullet}, \delta_{n-2, n-2}^{\bullet}\right)$.
Definition 6.3 (Cohomology). We can define the following two spaces

$$
\begin{gathered}
H_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}:=\frac{\operatorname{ker} \partial \oplus \bar{\partial} \cap A^{0,1} \oplus A^{1,0}}{d A^{0,0}} \\
H_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1}:=\frac{\operatorname{ker} d \cap A_{\mathrm{C}}^{2 n-1}}{d A^{n-1, n-1}}
\end{gathered}
$$

which are the cohomology spaces of the two complexes just defined. Note that by definition we have the inclusion

$$
H_{d R}^{1} \subseteq H_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}
$$

Definition 6.4 (Elliptic operators). We endow our almost complex manifold $(M, J)$ with an almost Hermitian metric $g$. We can write the formal adjoints of the operators in the complexes in Definition 6.2 as

$$
\begin{gathered}
A^{0,0} \stackrel{d^{*}}{\longleftarrow} A^{0,1} \oplus A^{1,0} \stackrel{d^{*}}{\longleftarrow} A^{1,1} \\
A^{n-1, n-1} \stackrel{\partial^{*}}{\rightleftarrows} \otimes^{\partial^{*}} A^{n-1, n} \oplus A^{n, n-1} \stackrel{d^{*}}{\longleftarrow} A^{n, n}
\end{gathered}
$$

The elliptic and formally self adjoint operators

$$
\begin{gathered}
\square_{B}^{1}: A^{0,1} \oplus A^{1,0} \rightarrow A^{0,1} \oplus A^{1,0} \\
\square_{B}^{2 n-1}: A^{n-1, n} \oplus A^{n, n-1} \rightarrow A^{n-1, n} \oplus A^{n, n-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

associated to the complexes are then defined by

$$
\begin{gathered}
\square_{B}^{1}:=d d^{*}+d^{*}(\partial \oplus \bar{\partial}) \\
\square_{B}^{2 n-1}:=d\left(\bar{\partial}^{*} \oplus \partial^{*}\right)+d^{*} d
\end{gathered}
$$

Remark 6.5 (Hodge theory). Assume that the almost Hermitian manifold $(M, J, g)$ is compact. It follows that the spaces of harmonic forms

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}:=\operatorname{ker} \square_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}=\operatorname{ker} d^{*} \cap \operatorname{ker} \partial \oplus \bar{\partial} \\
\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1}:=\operatorname{ker} \square_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1}=\operatorname{ker} d \cap \operatorname{ker} \bar{\partial}^{*} \oplus \partial^{*}
\end{gathered}
$$

have finite dimension $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}$ and $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1}$. Note that since

$$
\operatorname{ker} \Delta_{d}=\operatorname{ker} d \cap \operatorname{ker} d^{*}
$$

then there are inclusions

$$
\operatorname{ker} \Delta_{d} \cap A_{\mathrm{C}}^{k} \subseteq \mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{k}
$$

for $k=1,2 n-1$. Moreover, there are $L^{2}$ orthogonal decompositions

$$
\begin{gathered}
A_{\mathrm{C}}^{1}=\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{1} \oplus d A^{0,0} \oplus d^{*} A^{1,1} \\
A_{\mathrm{C}}^{2 n-1}=\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1} \oplus d A^{n-1, n-1} \oplus d^{*} A^{n, n}
\end{gathered}
$$

It follows that

$$
\operatorname{ker} \partial \oplus \bar{\partial} \cap A^{0,1} \oplus A^{1,0}=\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{1} \oplus d A^{0,0}
$$

$$
\operatorname{ker} d \cap A_{c}^{2 n-1}=\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1} \oplus d A^{n-1, n-1}
$$

therefore there are isomorphisms

$$
H_{\mathcal{B}}^{1} \simeq \mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}, \quad H_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1} \simeq \mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1}
$$

In particular the numbers $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}$ and $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1}$ are metric independent. The Hodge $*$ operator defines an isomorphism

$$
\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{1} \simeq \mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1}
$$

therefore $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}=h_{\mathcal{B}}^{2 n-1}$.
Remark 6.6 (Upper semi-continuity). By [KM06, Theorem 4.3, Chapter 4], on a given compact manifold, the dimension of the kernel of a smooth family of elliptic operators is upper semi-continuous. Therefore, it follows that $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}$ is upper semicontinuous along smooth deformations of the almost complex structure. The same result for $h_{p, q}^{k}$ on compact complex manifolds is shown in [Ste25, Corollary D].

Problem 6.7 (Explicit computation of $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}$ ). The first immediate problem is how to compute this new invariant $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}$ in explicit examples. When the almost complex structure $J$ is integrable, as we did in Section 4, there are many classes of nilmanifolds where the inclusion of left invariant forms into the de Rham algebra induces an isomorphism in the cohomology $H_{p, q}^{k}$.

It seems then reasonable to ask if there are as well classes of nilmanifolds carrying left invariant almost complex structures for which the inclusion of left invariant forms into the de Rham algebra induces an isomorphism in the cohomology $H_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}$.
Remark 6.8 (Other invariants defined via 1-forms). Let $(M, J, g)$ be a compact almost Hermitian manifold. We now describe two more invariants which can be defined using 1-forms, otherwise unrelated to $h_{\mathcal{B}}^{1}$, and argue about their ability in distinguishing maximally non-integrable almost complex structures of dimension at least 6 .

The invariant $h_{d+d^{c}}^{k} \in \mathbb{N}$ is defined in [ST23] as the dimension of the space $\operatorname{ker} \Delta_{d+d^{c}} \cap A^{k}$, where

$$
\Delta_{d+d^{c}}=d d^{c}\left(d d^{c}\right)^{*}+\left(d d^{c}\right)^{*} d d^{c}+d^{*} d^{c}\left(d^{*} d^{c}\right)^{*}+\left(d^{*} d^{c}\right)^{*} d^{*} d^{c}+d^{*} d+\left(d^{c}\right)^{*} d^{c}
$$

is an elliptic operator by [ST23, Proposition 4.3]. In [ST23, Proposition 4.7], it is proved that

$$
\operatorname{ker} \Delta_{d+d^{c}} \cap A^{1}=\operatorname{ker} d \cap \operatorname{ker} d^{c} \cap A^{1}
$$

and in particular $h_{d+d^{c}}^{1}$ is metric independent. By [ST23, Proposition 3.11], it follows that $h_{d+d^{c}}^{1}=2 h_{d}^{1,0}$, where $h_{d}^{1,0}$ here is the complex dimension of the space $\operatorname{ker} d \cap A^{1,0}$. As noted in [ST23, page 21], the invariant $h_{d+d^{c}}^{1}$ can distinguish between almost complex structures, but it cannot distinguish between maximally non-integrable almost complex structures on manifolds of dimension at least 6. Indeed, these assumptions imply that for all $x \in M$ the map

$$
\bar{\mu}_{x}: A_{x}^{1,0} \rightarrow A_{x}^{0,2}
$$

is injective, which forces $h_{d+d^{c}}^{1}=0$ [ST23, Proposition 4.10].
The invariant $h_{B C}^{p, q} \in \mathbb{N}$ is defined in [PT22] as the complex dimension of the space $\operatorname{ker} \tilde{\Delta}_{B C} \cap A^{p, q}$, where

$$
\tilde{\Delta}_{B C}=\partial \bar{\partial}(\partial \bar{\partial})^{*}+(\partial \bar{\partial})^{*} \partial \bar{\partial}+\partial^{*} \bar{\partial}\left(\partial^{*} \bar{\partial}\right)^{*}+\left(\partial^{*} \bar{\partial}\right)^{*} \partial^{*} \bar{\partial}+\partial^{*} \partial+\bar{\partial}^{*} \bar{\partial}
$$

is an elliptic operator by [PT22, Proposition 3.2]. It is immediate to see (see, e.g., [PT22, Section 3]) that

$$
\operatorname{ker} \tilde{\Delta}_{B C} \cap A^{1,0}=\operatorname{ker} \partial \cap \operatorname{ker} \bar{\partial} \cap A^{1,0}
$$

therefore $h_{B C}^{1,0}$ is metric independent. Note that, if $J$ is integrable, then $h_{B C}^{1,0}=h_{0,-1}^{0}$.

The two invariants $h_{d v d^{c}}^{1}$ and $h_{B C}^{1,0}$ are similarly defined, but nothing forces $h_{B C}^{1,0}$ to vanish on maximally non-integrable almost complex structures on manifolds of dimension at least 6 .

abstract:
Given a compact complex manifold, we develop Hodge theory for the elliptic
complex of differential forms defined by Bigolin in 1969 and recently referred
as the Schweitzer complex. We exhibit several $L^2$ orthogonal decompositions
of spaces of forms and prove a Hodge decomposition for harmonic forms on
compact K\"ahler manifolds. Then we compute the cohomology of this Bigolin
complex on the small deformations of the complex structure of the Iwasawa
manifold, showing that, in this example, this Bigolin cohomology is as powerful
as Aeppli and Bott-Chern cohomology, in order to distinguish complex
structures. Recall that the double complex of a compact complex manifold
decomposes into a direct sum of so-called squares and zigzags, and the zigzags
are the only components contributing to cohomology. We prove that, on any
compact complex manifold of complex dimension 3, the multiplicities of zigzags
in this decomposition are completely characterised by Betti, Hodge, Aeppli
numbers plus Bigolin numbers, namely the dimensions of the Bigolin cohomology.
This result is sharp, meaning that if we remove Hodge or Bigolin numbers from
the previous statement then it becomes false. We then apply this last result to
fully describe the double complexes of the small deformations of the Iwasawa
manifold. Finally, we partially extend the definition of this complex on almost
complex manifolds, providing a cohomological invariant on $1$-forms which is
finite dimensional when the manifold is compact.
